div.p:
Dieaes having an Affinity or holding Congruity with this we call thoe who at leat in part conit in the ame with the Eence of this Diea: of this kind are any cold ditemper, or any moit ditemper, alo any cold and moit ditemper. For a part of the firt Eence of this Diea includeth a cold and moit ditemper, and


o thoe ditempers do partly agree with this Affect. Hither alo belong a Phlegmatick Cachocymy, a Melancholy and a mixt; an obtruction proceeding from uch like humors, a Cachexia and a Dropy. Yea, we may likewie refer hither in regard of their affinity, thoe Dieaes wherein the inherent Spirits are omwhat conumed; for a part of the Eence of this Diea coniteth in a carity of thoe Spirits, but otherwie they are more aptly referred to the econd kind. In like manner the Dieaes wherin the firt affected parts are benummed, & tupified; may likewie in repect of their affinity, be hitherto referred, although they belong more properly to the third kind of Dieaes. Moreover, thoe Dieaes wherin the Tone of the parts is infeebled and looned mut here be lited, for they include a part of this Diea; namely, that which coniteth in the loonee, lithernes, internal lipperines and oftnes of the Tone, as they are above decribed. The Philoophers ay, that the Elements which agree in like qualities, are eaily changed one into another; by the ame reaon that thee Dieaes which partly agree in the ame Eence do eaily admit a reciprocal change from one to the other. So we ee a quotidian Ague, which agreeth with a putrid Feaver in a preternatural heat, upon every light Caue degenerate into it. Yet it mut here be noted, That great Dieaes are not o eaily changed into mal, as mal ones into great. Beides, not all Dieaes which perhaps participate alike of the ame Eence, are with an equal facility reciprocally changed. For ome Dieaes are more ubject to change into others, with whom in part they have ome agreement, than others: And that for other Reaons beide the aid agreement, however it be, if a cold and dry ditemper hould happen to a Child, that would eaily change into a cold and moit;


both in repect of the congruity of each Diea to cold, and alo a peculiar inclination of that tender age to moiture. For by reaon of the coldnes, the digetion becomes imperfect, and hereupon crudities or crude humidities are engendred, which a cold ditemper in o tender an age would eaily and immediatly follow. Moreover, a cold and moit ditemper in regard of the coldnes would make a low Pule, and in regard of the moiture would make it the more lippery, and the les vicous, wherupon the Vital heat being diminihed, a benummednes and dulnes by little and little would teal upon the Vital Spirits. Finally, in repect of that lipperih retention ariing from the internal lipperines of the parts, and by reaon of the weak concoction, the inherent Spirits of the firt affected parts, would alo by degrees be diminihed, and o by little and little after this manner the perfect Eence of this Diea wil be introduced.
